  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Introduction and Overview of the Daf: The Nazir's Impurity Restrictions",
      "display_title": "Intro & Overview",
      "timestamp": "00:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Opening remarks and announcement of today's coverage",
          "display_title": "Opening Remarks",
          "timestamp": "00:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "The focus of this perek: parameters of tumah for a nazir and exceptions to the rules",
          "display_title": "Perek Focus & Exceptions",
          "timestamp": "00:21"
        },
        {
          "title": "Practical relevance of tumah today only for those who take a nazir vow",
          "display_title": "Practical Relevance",
          "timestamp": "02:14"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Mishnah: First List of Impurities Causing the Nazir to Shave (Tumat Ohel)",
      "display_title": "First Impurity List",
      "timestamp": "02:27",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The first list of tumot: entire corpse, olive-sized flesh, netzel, decomposed matter, spinal cord, skull, limbs, half-kav of bones, half-log of blood",
          "display_title": "First List Items",
          "timestamp": "02:27"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tosafot on half-kav of bones: must come from majority of number or majority of structure",
          "display_title": "Half-Kav Bones",
          "timestamp": "08:38"
        },
        {
          "title": "Exception for quarter-kav of bones: causes tumat ohel but not nazir shaving; special halacha l'Moshe m'Sinai",
          "display_title": "Quarter-Kav Exception",
          "timestamp": "10:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "Three modes of tumah conduction: touching, carrying, and tent-over (ohel)",
          "display_title": "Three Modes of Tumah",
          "timestamp": "12:41"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Mishnah: Second List of Impurities (Contact Only, No Tent-Over)",
      "display_title": "Second Impurity List",
      "timestamp": "13:02",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Bone the size of a barley grain causes impurity through touch and carrying only, not through tent-over",
          "display_title": "Barley-Grain Bone",
          "timestamp": "13:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Consequences of impurity for the nazir: shaving, sprinkling ashes, destroying earlier days, bringing offerings",
          "display_title": "Consequences of Impurity",
          "timestamp": "13:48"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Gemara on the Mishnah: The Story of Rabbi Meir and the Troublemakers (Sumchos Incident)",
      "display_title": "Sumchos Incident",
      "timestamp": "15:48",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehuda's warning against Rabbi Meir's students: they are quarrelsome and debate halacha intellectually rather than sincerely",
          "display_title": "Yehuda's Warning",
          "timestamp": "15:48"
        },
        {
          "title": "Sumchos forces his way into the beit medrash and presents Rabbi Meir's version of the mishnah",
          "display_title": "Sumchos Forces Entry",
          "timestamp": "16:42"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehuda's objection: the redundancy of saying both 'corpse' and 'olive-sized flesh'",
          "display_title": "Yehuda's Objection",
          "timestamp": "17:17"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yosi's defense of Rabbi Meir: the necessity of both terms for a corpse without minimum flesh",
          "display_title": "Yosi's Defense",
          "timestamp": "18:26"
        },
        {
          "title": "Further discussion: Rabbi Yochanan on stillborn (nefel) without developed sinews",
          "display_title": "Nefel Discussion",
          "timestamp": "19:48"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rava's answer: small corpse with majority of structure but below minimum volume",
          "display_title": "Rava's Answer",
          "timestamp": "21:11"
        },
        {
          "title": "Reflection on the exchange: the importance of defending Torah over personalities",
          "display_title": "Torah vs. Personalities",
          "timestamp": "27:38"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Gemara on Netzel (Liquefied Flesh): Nature and Status for Impurity",
      "display_title": "Netzel Discussion",
      "timestamp": "28:19",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Definition of netzel: flesh that has dissolved and then recongealed, or juices that have boiled and congealed",
          "display_title": "Netzel Definition",
          "timestamp": "28:19"
        },
        {
          "title": "How congealing or boiling determines identity of netzel without requiring actual solidification",
          "display_title": "Identifying Netzel",
          "timestamp": "29:12"
        },
        {
          "title": "Abaye's question: does netzel exist for animal corpses and tumat neveilah, or only for tumat meis",
          "display_title": "Netzel for Animals",
          "timestamp": "32:45"
        },
        {
          "title": "The doctrine of tumat chamurah ad lager and tumat kalah ad lekelev: fitness for consumption determines status",
          "display_title": "Tumat Chamurah Doctrine",
          "timestamp": "34:07"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's conclusion: juices from decomposing flesh are not fit for human consumption, making the question moot",
          "display_title": "Question Moot",
          "timestamp": "37:33"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Mishnah on Pouring (Nitzok) and Connection of Foods",
      "display_title": "Nitzok Mishnah",
      "timestamp": "42:44",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "All pouring liquids are tahor: poured liquid does not connect to remaining liquid as one object",
          "display_title": "Pouring Not Connected",
          "timestamp": "42:44"
        },
        {
          "title": "Exceptions: very thick honey and beehive cakes are considered solid and do connect",
          "display_title": "Honey Exception",
          "timestamp": "43:30"
        },
        {
          "title": "Beit Shammai: even oatmeal and lentil porridge can connect if they pull back (soldes leachoreihen)",
          "display_title": "Beit Shammai View",
          "timestamp": "44:27"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Gemara on Nitzok for Foods: Does Liquefied Food Remain Connected as One Unit?",
      "display_title": "Nitzok for Foods",
      "timestamp": "45:40",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Question: does nitzok (pouring/separation) apply to foods, or are liquefied foods considered one connected unit",
          "display_title": "Nitzok Question",
          "timestamp": "45:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Two possible criteria: whether liquefied food has riri (sticky strands) or merely thickness",
          "display_title": "Two Criteria",
          "timestamp": "46:58"
        },
        {
          "title": "Proof from mishnah: fat of corpse liquefied remains tamei; separated and liquefied becomes tahor",
          "display_title": "Fat of Corpse Proof",
          "timestamp": "48:34"
        },
        {
          "title": "Question: if liquefied fat is not one connected unit (per nitzok), why is it still a source of impurity",
          "display_title": "Liquefied Fat Paradox",
          "timestamp": "50:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Zeira's answer: liquefied fat recongeals when flame reaches vessel opening",
          "display_title": "Rav Zeira Answer",
          "timestamp": "54:25"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ravina to Rav Ashi: Beit Shammai shows the criterion is riri (stickiness), not thickness; question remains unresolved",
          "display_title": "Ravina-Ashi Answer",
          "timestamp": "55:36"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
